threads.sub: Why is the fear of death so strong in younger generations?
threads.com: Being 30, death is just another meme. You go back to where you came from and you possibly reincarnate again or some shit. But you go back. To the whole. Memory wiped and everything. Bliss or permanent reincarnation, idk. But I don't understand why zoomers are afraid of it. You didn't like for 150k years and now it's about to be over retard, you are barely 20 years alive what the fuck are you trying so desperately to hold on to? What happens after death? Same thing that happened before it, idiot. I dont understand why most zoomers be like "yea I shit my pants each time I think of death" kek

last_replies.name: Anonymous
last_replies.com:
>>16522462
I'm 24 years old and I am not afraid of death. I am, however, afraid of dying. I love living. I'm invested in how this planet and society will progress as time passes by. I'm trying to stay relatively healthy to the best of my ability and knowledge.

Amongst my generation, it seems that suicide is more prevalent than ever before and the likelihood of attempting suicide is high. I have tempted suicide here or there and had a major panic attack once. Since going to therapy and watching videos about death, dying, and how insignificant everyone's lives, including my life, is in the grand scheme of things, I've since started to realize that suicide is pretty much pointless and not worth it. I recognize not everyone is living a life worth living and in shitty situations that make them want to kill themselves. I'm only speaking from my experience. I'd understand why someone would feel like committing suicide and recognize valid reasons to. I just don't find it worth doing, but that's just me.

Oh, and while as much as I'd like reincarnation to be real, I sort of don't want it to. To me, life is more interesting when you have a time limit to it. With the promise of death, you're forced to make every second count and find something worth living for and not waste time. I can't even understand how reincarnation would even work without the concept of souls being real, which I do not believe in. If souls did exist, though, then the idea that we would move from body to body after we die would be how I see reincarnation working.

Anyway, despite the pessimism about the future of my generation, I think we'll be fine (mostly). As humans, we are able to adapt to changes and our environments. Whatever dangerous and harmful stuff happens in the future, we'll be ready to solve any issues that happen (mostly).
